text.Taxonomy and naming:
Verticordia brevifolia was first formally described by Alex George in 1991 and the description was published in Nuytsia from specimens collected near Nyabing by Alex and Elizabeth George. The specific epithet (brevifolia) is derived from the Latin words brevis meaning "short" and folium meaning "leaf".There are two subspecies:

Verticordia brevifolia A.S.George subsp. brevifolia which has sepals and petals 3–3.5 mm (0.12–0.14 in) long and occurs in the Nyabing area;
Verticordia brevifolia subsp. stirlingensis A.S.George which has sepals and petals 4–5 mm (0.16–0.20 in) long and is only found in the Stirling Range area.George placed this species in subgenus Chrysoma, section Jugata along with V. chrysanthella, V. chrysantha, V. galeata, V. coronata, V. amphigia and V. laciniata.
